Lynas Rare Earths (LYC.AX) Price Target

Although many question the equity raising as a sign of peaking sentiment, the growth required in ex- China rare earth supply has a long runway. Investors have focussed on price bifurcation (now occurred), we think the medium term would emphasize expansion which the raising should help address. OW

In case you missed it... In a Global Insight led by the Australia Mining team (May 21 2025) we highlighted the urgent need for the formation of an ex- China bifurcated rare earths and magnets supply chain. Due to this, we used RE pricing as a key mechanism to solve for the winners, increased our LT NdPr price to US \(209 / kg\) and double upgraded LYC.

Why the equity raising and what will it be used for? LYC has chosen to raise equity in order to have the flexibility to expand at pace in a market which is rapidly changing. Since May 21, 2025, the three key exposures highlighted for rare earths are now up on average \(\sim 130\%\) , largely as the market has developed both the understanding and the appetite for this critical sector to grow. LYC wants to maintain its poll position in this sector, and it wants to do it through equity rather than debt to allow it both security and flexibility.

Use of funds 1 - Resource and Scale: In our March 13, 2024 initiation, we identified that LYC would benefit from utilizing its cracking and leaching (C&L) capability to capacity (Exhibit 1), for which Mt Weld over the long term, would need to expand production by 4ktpa. LYC has today allocated A \(\) 150\(m to focus on mine plan and grades at Mt Weld alongside new opportunities in ionic clays.

Use of funds 2 - Increase downstream capacity: Likewise, we identified the opportunity to add an extra 4.25ktpa over the long term in separating and finishing (assuming US at 1.25ktpa), for which LYC will allocate A \(\) 310\(m. In addition to this LYC has indicated developing a value - added specialty rare earth facility and expanding separation to 12ktpa.

Use of funds 3 - Metal and magnet supply chain expansion: A \(\) 200\(m will be allocated to expanding LYC's ex - China pricing framework and partnership opportunities, in line with the recently announced MoU with JS Link in Malaysia.
MORGAN STANLEY AUSTRALIA LIMITED+
Lynas Rare Earths (LYC.AX, LYC AU)

FY25 Result: FY25 saw the commissioning of Kalgoorlie and Mt Weld expansions, first production of separated heavy rare earths (Dy, Tb), and record NdPr output of \(\sim 6.5k\) tonnes. Full year revenue of \(\Delta\) 556.5m was slightly ahead \((+2.3\% / + 1.6\%\) vs MSe/VA Consensus), while EBITDA of \(\Delta\) 101.2m was broadly in line \((- 0.1\% / - 1.9\%)\) . NPAT of \(\Delta\) 8m was \(- 66.2\% / - 75.3\%\) vs MSe/Cons, on higher depreciation \((+21.4\% / + 33.0\%)\) due to Mt Weld ramp up. Operating cash flow of \(\Delta\) 104.2m beat \((+5.6\% / + 6.9\%)\) , but capex of A \(\Phi 430.8m\) drove FCF to \(- \Delta\) 326.7m, in line with expectations.

Model and valuation changes: We update our model for FY25 results, which causes our FY25 EPS to fall from \(\Delta\) 0.03/sh to \(\Delta\) 0.01/sh. We also incorporate the capital raising (A \(\Phi 750m\) placement \(+\) \(\Delta\) 75m share purchase plan) along with minor working capital adjustments. Overall, these estimate changes reduce our base case valuation by \(\Delta\) 0.30/sh, to \(\Delta\) 12.25/sh. Our bull case valuation rises \(\Delta\) 0.95/sh to \(\Delta\) 20.30, and our bear case valuation rises \(\Delta\) 1.75/sh, to \(\Delta\) 9.05/sh, on stronger liquidity post the capital raising, and lower sensitivity to our downside production scenario. We increase our bull weight, with our bull/base/bear weightings now \(35\% /55\% /10\%\) (prev. \(20\% /60\% /20\%\) ), due to NdPr prices currently above our base case forecast, and upside from potential expansion into NdFeB permanent magnet manufacturing (not in our base case). Overall, our price target rises \(\Delta\) 1.95/sh, to \(\Delta\) 14.75/sh (probability- weighted, DCF- based SotP).

Our ESG R/R tile includes data from FactSet, as well as, data from our proprietary HER score and Sustainable Solutions Interactive tool.

FactSet, a third party vendor, developed FactSet's SFDR Principal Adverse Impacts (PAI) data specifically to support compliant Sustainable Finance Disclosure Regulation (SFDR) reporting. FactSet collects PAI metrics from publicly available company disclosures, then standardizes the company- reported information to allow for easy comparison across companies. Specifically, FactSet converts nonconforming data points to standardized units as required by SFDR, like gigawatt hours, metric tons of CO2e, Tons and anti- corruption fines paid in EUR.

The Holistic Equal Representation (HER) score, a Morgan Stanley Research proprietary framework, systematically ranks companies on their level of gender diversity representation: the percentage of women who are (1) board members, (2) executives, (3) managers, and (4) employees. For each metric of representation, we calculated monthly region and sector (cohort) neutral z- scores which were then combined at an equal weight (25% each) to formulate HER Score. By using z- scored values, we are able to identify companies that are above or below their cohort mean. If any of the 4 metrics are missing for a company, the z- score for that metric is set to 0. Companies that rank the highest within their cohort will have the largest z- score and the those that rank the lowest will have the smallest (i.e. negative) z- score. Companies with the highest (lowest) z- scores across all 4 metrics will have the highest (lowest) HER Score. In Japan, we z- scored the equal weighted average of the raw metrics of representation by sector. We show which tertile each company is in for workforce gender diversity, relative to their regional sector peers.

Sustainable Solutions Interactive Tool, a Morgan Stanley Research proprietary tool, maps historical and projected revenue and capex exposure of stocks to sustainability themes. These sustainability themes include: Climate Change, Resource Management, Health & Wellbeing, Safety & Security, and Inclusion.
